Once everything is sewn then simply reassemble to the original metal frame. In this example, there were screws holding the armrests and top back sections to the metal frame:
Assemble all the pieces out on the floor to check that you have sewn together everything. If anything is missing at this stage, be sure to make it! {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9e/I9a-sml.jpg/460px-I9a-sml.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/9/9e/I9a-sml.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570.3564727954972,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Slip the pieces back on in the order required. This means that pieces that serve as the base or foundation will need to be in place first, then pieces that slip over the top are fed back into place next. The order will depend on the style of the chair. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/e/e3/I9b-sml.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/e/e3/I9b-sml.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":613,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":1013.3333333333334,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
